<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · What we do</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Cube ice is the most common commercial ice type. Bars, restaurants, hotels, cafés.</h2>

    <p>Bars use cube ice for cocktails. Restaurants for water service. Hotels for ice machines on every floor. Cafés for cold drinks. Capacity ranges from 200 lb/day undercounter machines (small bars, cafés) to 1,800+ lb/day modular machines on bins (hotels, hospitals, large restaurants).</p>

    <p>Our techs service cube ice machines across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. The three dominant brands in the LA market: <strong>Manitowoc Indigo NXT</strong> (Welbilt brand, IY series large modular, IB mid-size, ID compact undercounter), <strong>Hoshizaki KM-Edge</strong> (Japanese, KM-340MAJ small undercounter, KM-650MAJ mid, KM-901MAJ large), <strong>Scotsman Prodigy ELITE</strong> (Ali Group, C0322, C0530, C0630, C1030 sizes by lb production).</p>

    <p>Cube ice machines come in three architectural variants: <strong>vertical evaporator</strong> (water flows over plate, cubes form on plate, harvest cycle releases, Manitowoc style), <strong>horizontal evaporator with spray pump</strong> (water sprayed up onto evaporator from below, Scotsman style), and <strong>cell-and-curtain</strong> (water curtain over individual cube cells, Hoshizaki style). Different architectures have different repair patterns.</p>

    <p>EPA 608 Universal plus R-290 certified (post-2020 cube machines transitioning to R-290 hydrocarbon refrigerant). BHGS #A49573. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Parent context: <a href="/commercial/ice-machines/">commercial ice machine repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical cube ice machine failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Ten failure modes account for nearly every cube ice service call.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Scale buildup on evaporator → low ice production or no ice.</strong> Most common cube machine call. Cleaning resolves 50% of these. $200 to $340 service vs $1,500 to $3,000 evaporator replacement when scale destroys the evaporator.</li>
      <li><strong>Water inlet valve diaphragm degraded (year 5 to 8).</strong> Water flow reduced, ice production drops or stops entirely. Replacement $260 to $420.</li>
      <li><strong>Hot gas valve / harvest cycle issues.</strong> Ice frozen to evaporator, won't release during harvest. Hot gas valve failure or harvest sensor. $340 to $540 hot gas valve, $200 to $340 harvest sensor.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant slow leak (any age).</strong> EPA 608 leak repair before recharge. $700 to $1,500.</li>
      <li><strong>Condenser fan motor (air-cooled units, year 4 to 7).</strong> Replacement $300 to $520. Faster on coastal installs.</li>
      <li><strong>Bin sensor failure.</strong> Overflow despite full bin, or machine doesn't make ice when bin empty. $180 to $280.</li>
      <li><strong>Control board failure (year 8 to 12).</strong> Modern cube machines have sophisticated boards with diagnostic codes. $480 to $820.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor short-cycling.</strong> Refrigerant low, condenser dirty, or ambient temperature overload (kitchen at 95°F+ in summer).</li>
      <li><strong>Drain pan / drain line blockage.</strong> Water in bottom of bin, condensation overflow.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor mechanical wear (year 10 to 15).</strong> Replacement $1,400 to $2,800.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ARCHITECTURE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Three architectures, different repair patterns</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Vertical evap, horizontal spray, cell-and-curtain.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Vertical Evaporator (Manitowoc Indigo NXT style)</h3>
    <p>Water flows over a vertical evaporator plate from top down. Cubes form on the plate, harvest cycle uses warm water plus hot gas to release. Common failures: water distribution tube clogs, harvest valve, water pump.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Horizontal Evaporator with Spray Pump (Scotsman Prodigy ELITE style)</h3>
    <p>Water sprayed up onto the evaporator from a water trough below via spray pump. More efficient water use, but the spray pump is an additional failure point. Common failures: spray pump wear (year 6 to 9), spray nozzle clogs from scale.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Cell-and-Curtain (Hoshizaki KM-Edge style)</h3>
    <p>Water curtain over individual cube cells. Distinct cube formation. Common failures: water inlet pump, cell sensor, individual cell scale buildup (cleaning is critical).</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real repair stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · Manitowoc Indigo NXT IY-0454A modular cube + 400 lb bin, 6 years old, R-404A</h3>
      <p>Bar. Friday 8 PM no ice. Diagnosed: scale buildup on evaporator, last cleaning 18 months ago. Drained, applied Nu-Calgon Ice Machine Cleaner, ran cleaning cycle, sanitized, replaced water filter. Total: $120 plus $280 cleaning plus $160 filter = $560.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Hoshizaki KM-650MAJ undercounter cube, 8 years old</h3>
      <p>Restaurant. Refrigerant slow leak. EPA 608 leak repair: brazed evap joint, recharged R-404A. Total: $120 plus $480 refrigerant plus $720 labor plus leak detection = $1,420.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · Scotsman Prodigy ELITE C0530MA-1 cube + 400 lb bin, 10 years old</h3>
      <p>Hospital cafeteria. Control board error code F2 (water inlet valve fault). Replaced inlet valve. Cleared error code. Total: $120 plus $380 part plus 1.5 hours = $620.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Marina del Rey · Manitowoc Indigo NXT IB-0420A air-cooled cube, 7 years old</h3>
      <p>Hotel. Condenser fan motor seized (coastal salt). Replaced motor. Total: $120 plus $385 part plus 1 hour = $505.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · Ice-O-Matic ICE0500HA cube, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Coffee shop. Spray pump wear (Scotsman-style architecture). Pump failing intermittently, ice production dropping unpredictably. Replaced spray pump. Tested production over 6 hours. Total: $120 plus $440 part plus 2 hours = $720.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we do, and what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong> all major cube ice machine brands (Hoshizaki, Manitowoc, Scotsman, Ice-O-Matic, Follett, Kold-Draft for premium gourmet cube), all sizes (undercounter to large modular), air-cooled / water-cooled / remote-condensed, all refrigerants (R-22, R-134a, R-404A, R-290, we have R-290 certification), control board diagnostics on Manitowoc Indigo NXT / Hoshizaki KM-Edge / Scotsman Prodigy ELITE.</p>

    <p><strong>We don't do:</strong> new cube machine installation; ice bin standalone replacement; carbonated beverage system service on combination units (Cornelius beverage side, we service the ice side only).</p>

    <p>Knowing the boundary is part of being a real practitioner. Restaurant and hospitality operators value contractors who refer specialty work to specialists rather than fake competence.</p>
  </div>
</section>

